english:
  title: In Response to a Poem Left by Minister Wang at the Guest House in Jangsu
  author: Lim Yujung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    March blooms fade as twilight descends—
    I wander freely to Penglai Isle and meet the immortals.
    Beyond the railing, pine winds grow chill, the throat of the world constricts—
    Mountain light clinging to the town walls hangs sheer as silk.
    Fortunate to have clear wine enough to lose myself in revelry—
    Such worthy guests linger a while longer.
    Wherever we go, new verses spring forth—
    In my basket lie more than a hundred fresh poems.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This poem is composed in the style of a 'harmonizing response' (화답/和答), where the poet responds to a poem by Minister Wang using a parallel structure. Each couplet is attributed to different literati, suggesting a collaborative or allusive composition.
  - key: ''
    value: Penglai Isle (蓬萊島) is a legendary island of immortals in East Asian mythology, here used metaphorically for a place of refined gathering and inspiration.
  - key: ''
    value: The accumulation of 'more than a hundred poems' emphasizes the poetic productivity and creative energy of the gathering.
